  <!-- Main Content -->
  <article class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

        <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">
          Moving out of a rental in Huntsville, Alabama comes with one major stress beyond the boxes and logistics: getting your security deposit back. Whether you're leaving an apartment in downtown Huntsville, a townhome in Madison, or a house in Hampton Cove, property managers across Madison County have seen it all—and they know exactly where to look.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          This comprehensive guide covers everything Huntsville renters need to know about move-out cleaning, from what landlords actually inspect to the specific challenges of cleaning in the Tennessee Valley's unique climate.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Why Move-Out Cleaning Matters in Huntsville</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Huntsville's rental market has exploded over the past decade. With Redstone Arsenal, NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center, and the growing tech corridor bringing thousands of new residents, competition for quality rentals is fierce. Property management companies have become increasingly thorough in their move-out inspections—because they know they can fill your unit quickly and don't need to cut corners.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          The average security deposit in Madison County ranges from $1,000 to $2,500, depending on the property. That's real money—money that belongs to you if you leave the place in proper condition. The problem? Most tenants don't know what "proper condition" actually means to a property manager with a 47-point inspection checklist.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Huntsville-Specific Cleaning Challenges</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Living in the Tennessee Valley means dealing with environmental factors that don't exist in other parts of the country. Understanding these helps you prepare for a thorough move-out clean.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Alabama Red Clay</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          If you've lived anywhere near Big Cove, Owens Cross Roads, or the areas around Monte Sano, you know about Alabama red clay. This iron-rich soil doesn't just track into your home—it stains everything it touches. Check your entryways, garage floors, and any carpeted areas near exterior doors. That orange-red discoloration needs professional attention if regular cleaning doesn't remove it.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Humidity and Mold</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Huntsville's summer humidity creates perfect conditions for mold and mildew growth. Bathrooms, laundry areas, and any space near exterior walls are prime targets. Property managers will inspect grout lines, window seals, and under-sink areas carefully. If you see any dark spots or musty odors, address them before inspection day.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Pollen Season Residue</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Huntsville's infamous pollen season leaves a yellow-green coating on everything—including window tracks, screens, and exterior surfaces that are often part of move-out inspections. If you're moving out between March and May, pay extra attention to anything exposed to outside air.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Hard Water Deposits</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Much of Madison County has hard water, which leaves mineral deposits on faucets, showerheads, glass shower doors, and around drains. These white, chalky buildups are a common deduction item that many tenants overlook.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">What Huntsville Property Managers Actually Inspect</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          We've worked with tenants from properties managed by every major company in Madison County. Here's what they all have in common when it comes to inspections:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Kitchen Deep Dive</h3>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li><strong>Inside the oven and broiler drawer:</strong> They pull out the drawer and look underneath. Grease splatter on the oven walls is an automatic charge.</li>
          <li><strong>Range hood and vent filters:</strong> These are often forgotten and almost always greasy.</li>
          <li><strong>Refrigerator interior, including rubber door gaskets:</strong> Mold in the gasket folds is a common find.</li>
          <li><strong>Under and behind appliances:</strong> They move the refrigerator and stove to check.</li>
          <li><strong>Dishwasher interior and drain filter:</strong> The filter at the bottom collects food particles over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Cabinet interiors, including above the refrigerator:</strong> Dust and debris accumulate in unused cabinets.</li>
          <li><strong>Garbage disposal area:</strong> Splash residue and odors.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Bathroom Inspection Points</h3>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li><strong>Toilet base, behind, and under the tank:</strong> They check every angle.</li>
          <li><strong>Shower/tub grout and caulking:</strong> Discoloration or mildew means charges.</li>
          <li><strong>Exhaust fan cover:</strong> Dust accumulation is extremely common.</li>
          <li><strong>Under bathroom sinks:</strong> Checking for water damage signs and cleanliness.</li>
          <li><strong>Medicine cabinet interior and mirror:</strong> Both surfaces matter.</li>
          <li><strong>Shower door tracks:</strong> Soap scum and hard water deposits build up here.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Living Areas and Bedrooms</h3>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li><strong>All baseboards:</strong> Dust, scuffs, and pet damage.</li>
          <li><strong>Window tracks and blinds:</strong> Both sides of every blind slat.</li>
          <li><strong>Light fixtures and ceiling fans:</strong> Top of fan blades, inside light covers.</li>
          <li><strong>HVAC vents and returns:</strong> Dust buildup is visible and documented.</li>
          <li><strong>Closet shelves, floors, and walls:</strong> Every closet, including coat closets.</li>
          <li><strong>Door frames and top of doors:</strong> Dust accumulates where you don't look.</li>
          <li><strong>Carpet condition:</strong> Beyond normal wear—stains, pet damage, burns.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Neighborhood-Specific Considerations</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Different areas of Huntsville have their own quirks when it comes to move-out cleaning. Here's what to watch for based on where you're moving from:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Downtown Huntsville & Five Points</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Older buildings in downtown and the Five Points area often have original hardwood floors that require special care. Don't use excessive water—these floors can warp. Watch for paint condition on original trim and windowsills. Many of these buildings also have older HVAC systems with visible ductwork that accumulates dust.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Madison & Madison City</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Madison has seen massive new construction, meaning many rentals are in newer subdivisions like Providence, Heritage Plantation, or Bradford Creek. These properties often have builder-grade fixtures that show wear quickly and HOA inspections that complement landlord inspections. Pay attention to garage floors (oil stains are common deductions) and landscaping bed areas visible from the home.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Hampton Cove & Big Cove</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Properties in the cove areas tend to be larger single-family homes with more square footage to clean. Many have screened porches or three-season rooms that are included in move-out inspections. The proximity to the mountains means more pollen and leaf debris in gutter-adjacent areas. These properties also commonly have irrigation systems—make sure any controllers or timers are clean and properly set.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Research Park & Jones Valley</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          The apartment complexes and townhomes near Research Park cater heavily to defense contractors and tech workers—often furnished or semi-furnished units with appliances included. Make sure every appliance is cleaned inside and out. These properties also tend to have shared amenity spaces where your move-out doesn't impact common areas, but your individual unit inspection is typically more detailed.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Harvest & Meridianville</h3>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          The rapid development in Harvest and Meridianville means many rentals are in new subdivisions with active construction nearby. Dust from construction can infiltrate homes and settle on every surface. If you're in one of these areas, plan for extra dusting on all horizontal surfaces, inside cabinets, and on top of ceiling fan blades.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">The Cost of Getting It Wrong</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Huntsville property managers don't charge what things actually cost—they charge what their "preferred vendors" bill, often with markup. Here are real deduction examples we've seen from Madison County properties:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-600">
          <li>Oven cleaning: $75-125 (takes us 20-30 minutes)</li>
          <li>Refrigerator cleaning: $50-100</li>
          <li>"General cleaning": $200-500 (vague but common)</li>
          <li>Carpet cleaning: $150-300 per room</li>
          <li>Blind cleaning/replacement: $25-75 per window</li>
          <li>Full deep clean: $400-800</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">
          Add these up and you can easily lose your entire deposit over issues that a proper move-out clean would have prevented.
        </p>

        <!-- Mid-Article CTA -->
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-gray-900 to-gray-800 rounded-2xl p-8 my-10 text-center">
          <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-2">Don't risk your deposit</p>
          <p class="text-gray-300 mb-6">Move-out cleaning from $199. We know exactly what Madison County property managers check — and we make sure it passes.</p>
